Murang&rsquo;a Senator Kembi Gitura has expressed alarm the county has been identified as a likely hotspot during nominations and the General Election. He told journalists on Wednesday in Murang&rsquo;a town it&rsquo;s unfortunate the county has become a flashpont due to intolerance among aspirants.Kembi, who is also the Senate Deputy Speaker, said Murang&rsquo;a is a homogenous county, known for hardworking and peaceful people.He said politicians must respect each other and stop hooligans causing confrontations among supporters. &ldquo;This is the only way we can build a strong democracy and show our children it is possible to have peaceful elections,&rdquo; Kembi said.The senator said the report released by the National Democracy Authority shows Murang&rsquo;a is one of the 40 areas that could experience violence.CLAMOUR FOR JP TICKETSHe called this shocking and a wake-up call.&ldquo;I&rsquo;m hoping it is not true, but if it is, I&rsquo;m requesting all aspirants to ensure peaceful Jubilee Party nominations on April 21,&rdquo; Kembi said.The majority of aspirants in the county are seeking the JP ticket.However, while some plan to leave the party and run as independents for fear of rigged elections.He said he doesn&rsquo;t understand why Murang&rsquo;a in the heart of Central Kenya has been singled out as a trouble spot, adding that&rsquo;s unheard of.Kembi urged security agents to be on high alert.&ldquo;We should all endeavour to bring to an end the culture of violence in the county and country so it will not be experienced in the future,&rdquo; the senator said.Kembi also urged those who aggrieved over nomination results to lodge complaints with the Political Parties&rsquo; Tribunal, instead of engaging in violence.He said Murang&rsquo;a did not experience violence during the times of Dr Julius Kiano and Kenneth Matiba, when political temperatures were high.Since the Mau Mau, he said, the county has never experienced political bloodshed and it would be unfortunate for it to happen now.&ldquo;Politics is a matter of being elected and people should not engage in physical fights for it.&ldquo;Politics is not a matter of life or death,&rdquo; the senator said.